<section id="masala-study">
    <h2>The MASALA Study</h2>

    <p>The <strong>MASALA Study</strong> (Mediators of Atherosclerosis in South Asians Living in America) is a landmark research program studying why South Asians have such high rates of cardiovascular disease.</p>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Why This Study Matters</h3>
        <p>South Asians (people with ancestry from India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal) have 2-4x higher rates of heart disease than other ethnic groups - often at younger ages and lower body weights. Until MASALA, no one was systematically studying why.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Study Design</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Participants:</strong> 900+ South Asian Americans from the San Francisco Bay Area and Chicago</li>
        <li><strong>Ages:</strong> 40-84 years at enrollment</li>
        <li><strong>Started:</strong> 2010</li>
        <li><strong>Comprehensive assessments:</strong> CT scans, blood tests, lifestyle questionnaires, dietary assessment</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Unique Focus Areas</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Body composition:</strong> Fat distribution at different BMI levels</li>
        <li><strong>Metabolic markers:</strong> Insulin resistance, liver fat</li>
        <li><strong>Subclinical disease:</strong> Coronary artery calcium before symptoms</li>
        <li><strong>Lifestyle factors:</strong> Diet, physical activity, acculturation</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="research">
    <h2>Key Research Findings</h2>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Dr. Kanaya's Core Message</h3>
        <blockquote>
            "South Asians are having heart attacks at younger ages and at lower BMIs than any other group. Our standard risk calculators completely miss this. The MASALA study is showing us that we need South Asian-specific guidelines - the current ones are failing this population."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>Major MASALA Findings</h3>

    <h4>1. BMI Underestimates Risk</h4>
    <p>Standard BMI cutoffs don't work for South Asians:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>South Asians develop metabolic disease at <strong>BMI 23</strong> (vs. 25 for Europeans)</li>
        <li>Even "normal weight" South Asians often have high body fat percentage</li>
        <li>Visceral (belly) fat is elevated even at lower BMIs</li>
        <li><strong>Recommended cutoffs:</strong> Overweight at BMI 23, Obese at BMI 27.5</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>2. Coronary Artery Calcium is Common</h4>
    <p>MASALA found high rates of subclinical atherosclerosis:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>43% had detectable coronary artery calcium</li>
        <li>Present even in relatively young participants</li>
        <li>Higher than predicted by standard risk calculators</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>3. Metabolic Syndrome is Rampant</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>46% of MASALA participants had metabolic syndrome</li>
        <li>High rates of fatty liver disease</li>
        <li>Insulin resistance common even without diabetes</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>4. Standard Risk Calculators Fail</h4>
    <p>The ACC/AHA risk calculator significantly underestimates risk in South Asians, missing many who would benefit from preventive treatment.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>The Critical Issue</h3>
        <p>South Asians look "healthy" by Western standards - normal BMI, no diabetes - but have high rates of insulin resistance, visceral fat, and subclinical atherosclerosis. Without ethnic-specific screening, they're not identified as high risk until after a heart attack.</p>
    </div>
</section>

